      'Attorney Diane Foster contacts you regarding a complex gifting transaction. Her client, George Lambert (age 80), owns a historic 5-bedroom, 4-bath Victorian home on 3 acres in a nationally registered historic district. Mr. Lambert plans to transfer the property to a family trust for the benefit of his grandchildren while retaining a life estate. The property has several complicating factors: (1) an existing mortgage of $185,000, (2) a historic preservation easement (donated 15 years ago) that restricts exterior modifications and requires maintenance consistent with the Secretary of the Interior\'s Standards, (3) a property line dispute with the adjacent neighbor that has been in litigation for 2 years with no resolution (involving approximately 0.15 acres along the western boundary), and (4) a Phase I Environmental Site Assessment conducted last year identified a recognized environmental condition (REC) — a former underground storage tank from a prior use — that has not been further investigated. The attorney needs the fair market value for gift tax purposes and asks you to address how each complicating factor affects value.',
