      scope_of_work: 'Complete narrative appraisal addressing each complicating factor. (1) HISTORIC PRESERVATION EASEMENT: The easement is already in place and restricts the property. The appraisal must reflect the property AS ENCUMBERED by the easement. Comparable sales should ideally be properties in historic districts with similar restrictions. If unavailable, the appraiser must adjust for the restrictions (limited exterior modification ability, maintenance requirements, potential cost of compliance). (2) BOUNDARY DISPUTE: The appraiser must address the unresolved litigation. Options include: (a) value the property excluding the disputed 0.15 acres (conservative, with an EA stating the dispute will not be resolved in the owner\'s favor), (b) value it including the full acreage (with an EA that the dispute will be resolved favorably), or (c) provide both values. The appraiser should discuss with the attorney which assumption to apply. The unresolved dispute itself may reduce marketability even beyond the acreage in question. (3) ENVIRONMENTAL REC: The Phase I identified a REC but no Phase II investigation has been conducted. The appraiser must address the potential environmental liability. Without a Phase II, the actual contamination (if any) and remediation cost are unknown. The appraiser may: apply a market-supported discount for environmental uncertainty, recommend a Phase II before completing the appraisal, or invoke an EA about the environmental condition. (4) HISTORIC PROPERTY VALUATION: Must understand the local market for historic homes, including the premium or discount the market applies to nationally registered properties (historic designation can add value through prestige and tax credits, or reduce value through maintenance burdens and modification restrictions). Sales comparison approach is primary; cost approach requires understanding of historic construction and functional obsolescence.',
      assumptions: 'Multiple Extraordinary Assumptions and Hypothetical Conditions likely needed: EA (1): Regarding the boundary dispute — the appraiser must state the assumption about whether the disputed 0.15 acres is included or excluded and its basis. EA (2): Regarding the environmental REC — without a Phase II, the appraiser may assume no significant contamination exists (but this EA must be clearly stated and its impact on the value conclusion discussed, per USPAP), OR the appraiser may assume contamination exists and estimate a discount — the choice depends on direction from the attorney and available evidence. EA (3): The historic preservation easement terms are as described and recorded. Limiting Conditions: The appraiser is not an environmental consultant and cannot determine whether contamination exists or estimate remediation costs; the appraiser is not a surveyor or attorney and cannot determine the outcome of the boundary dispute; the appraiser relies on the Phase I report, the easement document, and the survey for factual information.',
      uspap: 'Standards Rule 1 and 2; IRS qualified appraisal and qualified appraiser requirements; this assignment triggers significant Competency Rule considerations — the appraiser must be competent in historic property valuation, environmental impact analysis (at the appraisal level, not the environmental science level), boundary/title dispute impact analysis, and preservation easement valuation; if the appraiser lacks competency in any area, they must either acquire it, associate with a qualified appraiser, or withdraw from the assignment; Ethics Rule — with so many complicating factors, each assumption the appraiser makes can significantly swing the value, and the donor or attorney may have preferences; the appraiser must make independent, supportable judgments; the IRS will closely scrutinize an appraisal with this many extraordinary assumptions; USPAP requires the appraiser to determine that each EA is credible — an EA that is not reasonable effectively undermines the appraisal; Advisory Opinions 9 (environmental) and 34 may be relevant; the appraiser should strongly recommend that the Phase II ESA and the boundary litigation be resolved before completing the appraisal, as the value conclusion will be significantly more reliable with that information',
